/>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Past tense:</span></p><p>The bear <span class=\"marker\">walked</span> out of the are talking about two events that happened in the past. If one event was completed before the other one started, use<em> had</em> with the verb.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Two events that happened in the past:</span></p><p>I <span class=\"marker\">had just put out</span> the trash when the raccoon <span class=\"marker\">came </span>after me. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Just put out is the first event to occur in the past and is preceded by had. The raccoon came after me is the second event to occur. Came is the past tense verb.</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"10"},"leftText":"<p>If you are talking&nbsp; about a single event that happened in the past, use the past tense.&nbsp; Do not include&nbsp;<em> had</em>.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Single event in the past:</span></p><p>The raccoon <span class=\"marker\">came </span>after me. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Came is the past tense verb.</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"11"},"leftText":"<p>Some verbs form the past tense in different ways.<br />&nbsp;</p><p>The past tense of these verbs does not follow a pattern. Each one is formed in its own way.&nbsp; To find the past tense of a verb you do not recognize, you should look it up in a dictionary.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tablesmall-pad\" style=\"width:100%;\"><caption><strong>VERBS THAT DO NOT FOLLOW A PATTERN</strong></caption><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\"><strong>Present&nbsp; Tense</strong></th><th scope=\"col\"><strong>Past Tense</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>say</td><td>said</td></tr><tr><td>do</td><td>did</td></tr><tr><td>run</td><td>ran</td></tr><tr><td>hold</td><td>held</td></tr><tr><td>come</td><td>came</td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"12"},"leftText":"<p>The <strong>future tense</strong> shows actions that will happen in the future.<br /><br /><strong>How to form it:</strong>&nbsp; Use the helping verb, <em>will</em>, to form the future tense.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Future tense:</span></p><p>The bear <span class=\"marker\">will return</span> to his home in the woods <span class=\"marker\">tomorrow.</span>&nbsp;<span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Tomorrow shows the events will happen in the future. The helping verb will is added to the verb return to form the future tense.</span></p>","headerText":"Future tense"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"13"},"leftText":"<p>When you write, think about <strong>when</strong> the events occurred and in <strong>what order</strong> they occurred.&nbsp; Use the different tenses to make this clear to your reader.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"For events that happened in the past, use the past tense: The bear rushed.  For events happening now, use the present tense: The bear rushes, or the bear is rushing. For events that will happen in the future, use the future tense:  The bear will rush.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"Showing when events happen"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"14"},"leftText":"<p>You may need to change&nbsp;verb tense while writing in an effort to explain the order in which events happened.&nbsp; Sometimes you might start in the present tense and shift to the past tense.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Shifting from present to past tense:</span></p><p>I <span class=\"marker\">am happy</span> because he <span class=\"marker\">brought</span> me flowers. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Am happy is the present tense verb. Brought is the past tense verb.</span></p><p>Jen <span class=\"marker\">tells</span> us, &quot;I <span class=\"marker\">was</span> lucky to be alive.&quot; <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Tells is the present tense verb. Was is the past tense verb.</span></p>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"15"},"leftText":"<p>Sometimes you might begin writing&nbsp;in the past and switch to the future.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Shifting from past to future tense:</span></p><p>A reporter <span class=\"marker\">noticed</span> suspicious paw prints, so everyone in town <span class=\"marker\">will watch</span> for unusual activity. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Noticed is the past tense verb. Will watch is the future tense verb.</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"16"},"leftText":"<p><strong>Tip:&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;After&nbsp;you write something, read it over one extra time to be sure you have used the tenses that tell exactly when all the events occurred or will occur.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"17"},"leftText":"<p>Sometimes changing tense is not appropriate.&nbsp; When you are sharing information that does not rely on time, choose one tense and use it throughout your writing.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /><br />If you are writing about an event that did happen at a specific point of time, choose your tense and be careful not to shift it without having a valid reason for doing so.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null,"headerText":"When to stick to one tense"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"18"},"leftText":"<p>Look at the original news story about the black bear sighting.&nbsp;<br /><br />This occurred last Sunday evening, showing that the action reported in the story happened in the past.&nbsp;&nbsp; The verbs<em> reported, occurred, was, </em>and<em> walked </em>are all past tense.<br /><br />Notice that<em> steps, stands</em>, <em>startles, </em>and<em> backs </em>are in the present tense.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<table border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain ju-tight\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Black Bear Sighting!</strong></p><p>Neighbors in the Johnson Road area of town <span class=\"marker\">reported</span> a bear sighting.&nbsp; The sighting <span class=\"marker\">occurred</span> last Sunday evening, just after dark.&nbsp; Jen Williams <span class=\"marker\">was</span> home alone when she <span class=\"marker\">steps</span> outside.&nbsp; Suddenly, a black bear <span class=\"marker\">walked</span> out of the woods.&nbsp; Jen described how she <span class=\"marker\">stands</span> still, afraid to move, as&nbsp;the bear moved toward her swimming pool.&nbsp; All of a sudden, the bear rushed at Jen and <span class=\"marker\">startles</span> her.&nbsp; Jen <span class=\"marker\">backs</span> away and called 911.&nbsp; Jen tells us, &quot; I was lucky to be alive!&quot;&nbsp;</p></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"19"},"leftText":"<p>The writer has shifted the tense for no reason.&nbsp; All the verbs except for those in the last sentence should be in the past tense.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">All verbs should be in the past tense:</span></p><p><span class=\"ju-orangetimesph\" style=\"color:#F79A1F;font-weight:bold;\">x</span><span class=\"ju-examples\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:tahoma;\"> </span>Jen described how she <span class=\"marker\">stands</span> still, afraid to move, as the bear moved toward her swimming pool. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Stands is the incorrect present tense verb.</span></p><p><span class=\"ju-greencheckph\" style=\"color:#08A47D;font-weight:bold;\">v</span><span class=\"ju-examples\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:tahoma;\"> </span>Jen described how she <span class=\"marker\">stood</span> still, afraid to move, as the bear moved toward her swimming pool. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Stood is the correct past tense verb.</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"20"},"leftText":"<p>When a sentence has multiple parts, you may have trouble deciding which tense to use.&nbsp; Remember, if the events being described happened at the same time, use the same tense.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Events happening at the same time should use the same tense:</span></p><p><span class=\"ju-orangetimesph\" style=\"color:#F79A1F;font-weight:bold;\">x</span> Jen <span class=\"marker\">walked</span> out of the house, <span class=\"marker\">stood</span> on the deck, and <span class=\"marker\">sees</span> a bear. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Walked and stood are in the past tense.&nbsp; Sees is in the present tense and is not correct.</span></p><p><span class=\"ju-greencheckph\" style=\"color:#08A47D;font-weight:bold;\">v</span> Jen <span class=\"marker\">walked</span> out of the house,<span class=\"marker\"> stood</span> on the deck, and <span class=\"marker\">saw</span> a bear. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">The verbs walked, stood, and saw are all in the past tense and correct.</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"21"},"leftText":"<p>The last sentence of the story is describing something Jen said to the reporter in the present, but she is talking about something that happened in the past.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /><br />It starts in the present, and shifts to the past.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Starts in the present and shifts to the past:</span></p><p>Jen<span class=\"marker\"> tells</span> us, &quot;I <span class=\"marker\">was</span> lucky to be alive!&quot; <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">The verb tells&nbsp;describes something happening in the present. The verb was describes something that happened in the past.</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"22"},"leftText":"<p>When using verbs, understanding which word to use for the present and past tense can be difficult, especially when the words sound the same.</p><p>To choose the correct word, think about what you are trying to say, and whether you are telling about the present or the past.<br /><br /><em>Lay</em> and<em> lie</em> are two different verbs with two different meanings:<br /><br /><em>Lay </em>means to put or place something.<br /><br /><em>Lie </em>means to rest in a reclining position.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Lie vs. lay:</span></p><p>Jen <span class=\"marker\">lays</span> the book on the table. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">The present tense verb lays describes the book being placed on the table in the present.</span></p><p>The bear <span class=\"marker\">lies</span> on his back in the swimming pool. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">The present tense verb lies describes the bear resting in a reclining position in the present.</span></p>","headerText":"Avoiding common errors"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"23"},"leftText":"<p>The past tense of the verb <em>lie</em> is <em>lay</em>.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /><br />The past tense of the verb&nbsp;<em>lay</em> is <em>laid</em>.<br />&nbsp;</p><table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-powertip\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\">Careful!</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><p>Do not use<em> laid</em> for the past tense of <em>lie</em>, use <em>lay</em>.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Present tense:</span></p><p>Today, the bear <span class=\"marker\">lies</span> on his back in the swimming pool.<br /><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Past tense:</span></p><p><span class=\"ju-orangetimesph\" style=\"color:#F79A1F;font-weight:bold;\">x</span>&nbsp; Yesterday, the bear <span class=\"marker\">laid</span> on his back in the swimming pool. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Laid is the past tense of the verb lay, meaning to put or place something.</span></p><p><span class=\"ju-greencheckph\" style=\"color:#08A47D;font-weight:bold;\">v</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;Yesterday, the bear <span class=\"marker\">lay</span> on his back in the swimming pool. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Lay is the past tense of the verb lie, meaning to rest in a reclining position.</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"24"},"leftText":"<p><em>Choose </em>and<em> chose </em>are two forms of the same verb:<br /><br /><em>Choose </em>means to select one option from a group<br /><br /><em>Chose </em>is the past tense of choose.<br /><br />To make sure you are using the correct word, think about whether you are telling about the present or the past.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Present /><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Past tense:</span></p><p>Yesterday, I <span class=\"marker\">chose</span> to stay home and watch for the bear. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Chose is the past tense verb.</span></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":"0","audioPath":"25"},"leftText":"<p>Sometimes words are confusing because they <em>lead.</em><br /><br /><em>Lead ( </em>rhymes with <strong>bed</strong>) is a metallic element.&nbsp;&nbsp; It sounds the same as <em>led</em>!<br /><br />To choose the correct word, think about what you are trying to say, and whether you are telling about the present or the past.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Present tense:</span></p><p>Please <span class=\"marker\">lead</span> the team onto the field now. <span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Lead is the present tense verb.</span><br /><br /><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Past
